Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Can you please review the code? evel.c calls evel_batch.c with this piece of code:

    case EVEL_DOMAIN_BATCH:
      EVEL_DEBUG("Event is a Batch at %lp", evt_ptr);
      evel_free_batch((EVENT_HEADER *)evt_ptr);
      memset(evt_ptr, 0, sizeof(EVENT_HEADER));
      free(evt_ptr);
      break;

the pointer is freed twice, which will cause an issue

Patch Set 1:

> Can you please review the code? evel.c calls evel_batch.c with this
 > piece of code:
 > 
 > case EVEL_DOMAIN_BATCH:
 > EVEL_DEBUG("Event is a Batch at %lp", evt_ptr);
 > evel_free_batch((EVENT_HEADER *)evt_ptr);
 > memset(evt_ptr, 0, sizeof(EVENT_HEADER));
 > free(evt_ptr);
 > break;
 > 
 > the pointer is freed twice, which will cause an issue

Though both pointers passed to functions are same, but each does the different thing. 
evel_free_batch(evt_ptr) -> frees all contained events, and the newly called evel_free_header(..) function frees the header part of the batch event.

free(evt_ptr) -> this function in evel.c as mentioned by you would free the evt_ptr only. The rest of functions were freeing memory pointed by evt_ptr (i.e. header + batch events). 

To test this, I have commented the free(evt_ptr) and tried running the valgrind, I see that 384 bytes are being lost because of this. So free(evt_ptr) is needed which is not duplicate.
